REvil Ransomware Lab | CyberDefenders
Overview

This repository contains my complete writeup from the REvil - GOLD SOUTHFIELD lab on CyberDefenders. The lab simulates a real-world ransomware incident response scenario where I 
investigate an encrypted machine using Splunk SIEM and Sysmon event logs to extract indicators of compromise and reconstruct the attack chain.

Scenario

As a Threat Hunter for a cybersecurity consulting firm, I analyzed one of several machines encrypted in a ransomware attack. The affected users reported ransom notes on their desktops 
and changed background images. My task was to use Splunk to extract as much information as possible about the attack.
Key Findings

Through the investigation, I answered six core questions:

    Ransom Note Filename — Identified the note left behind by the ransomware
    Process ID — Pinpointed the ransomware's process ID from event logs
    Executable Location — Located the ransomware executable and identified the attack vector
    Shadow Copy Deletion — Deobfuscated a Base64-encoded PowerShell command disabling system recovery
    SHA256 Hash — Extracted and validated the ransomware hash against threat intelligence
    C2 Domain — Identified the attacker's Tor-based command and control infrastructure using VirusTotal and AnyRun

Skills Practiced

    Splunk querying and log analysis
    Sysmon event log investigation
    Base64 deobfuscation and command analysis
    Hash validation and threat intelligence correlation
    Attack timeline reconstruction
    IOC identification and verification

What I Learned

This lab reinforced practical SOC workflow: moving between SIEM queries and external threat intelligence platforms to validate findings. 
Leveraging built-in features like Splunk's Interesting Fields made investigation significantly more efficient than manual queries in this instance.
